<description>
<div>Pengnan, litteraly the south (nan) of Penghu (peng) is a peninsular and part of the Penghu island. Shaped like a V, or a bowl, it is located to the south of Magong and protects Magong from winds of waves coming from south or southeast. Similarly to Xiyu it has been of military importance for the protection of Magong. It is here where the Dutch built their fort and thus irritated to Qing government. Later KMT soldiers were stationed in the same spot, eventually destroying a site that should have been marked and reserved as a heritage and potential archeological site. Fortunately for the inhabitants of Pengnan, winds and waves coming from the south represent a real problem in combination with taiphoons. However places like Shili are extremely exposed to environmental threats and one might wonder, why people settled there and how they managed to cope.</div><include href="tmlDocTaiwanPenghuFenggui.xml" parse="xml"/><include href="tmlDocTaiwanPenghuJingan.xml" parse="xml"/><include href="tmlDocTaiwanPenghuTiexian.xml" parse="xml"><stats><stat type="cemetery" direct="1" indirect="1" cross="0">2</stat><stat type="earthgod" indirect="11" direct="0" cross="0">11</stat><stat type="photo" indirect="2" direct="0" cross="0">2</stat><stat type="tomb" indirect="56" direct="0" cross="0">56</stat><stat type="tombstone" indirect="54" direct="0" cross="0">54</stat></stats></include><include href="tmlDocTaiwanPenghuShanshui.xml" parse="xml"><stats><stat type="cemetery" direct="2" indirect="1" cross="0">3</stat><stat type="earthgod" indirect="81" direct="0" cross="0">81</stat><stat type="grave" indirect="4" direct="0" cross="0">4</stat><stat type="house" direct="1" indirect="0" cross="0">1</stat><stat type="memorial" direct="2" indirect="0" cross="0">2</stat><stat type="photo" indirect="4" direct="0" cross="0">4</stat><stat type="shigandang" direct="1" indirect="0" cross="0">1</stat><stat type="tomb" indirect="181" direct="0" cross="0">181</stat><stat type="tombstone" indirect="279